✅ Step 2: Fetch Solar Irradiance Data via API

Here’s an example Python script to get 15-min interval irradiance (GHI, DNI, DHI) for a location like Jaipur, India:

python
import requests
import pandas as pd

API_KEY = 'YOUR_API_KEY'  # Replace with your actual key
LAT, LON = 26.9124, 75.7873  # Jaipur coordinates
DATE = '2025-06-01'

url = f"https://api.openweathermap.org/energy/2.0/solar/interval_data"
params = {
    "lat": LAT,
    "lon": LON,
    "date": DATE,
    "interval": "15m",
    "appid": API_KEY
}

response = requests.get(url, params=params)
data = response.json()

# Extracting and formatting data
df = pd.DataFrame(data["data"])
df["dt"] = pd.to_datetime(df["dt"], unit="s")
print(df[["dt", "ghi", "dni", "dhi"]].head())

📘 2_Forecasting_Prophet.py – Forecasting SOC with Prophet

python
# Prophet Forecasting for State of Charge (SOC)
from prophet import Prophet
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load simulated data
df = pd.read_csv('../data/soc_simulated.csv')
df['ds'] = pd.to_datetime(df['datetime'])
df['y'] = df['SOC (%)']

# Initialize and fit the model
model = Prophet(daily_seasonality=True)
model.fit(df[['ds', 'y']])

# Make future dataframe and forecast
future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=48, freq='15min')
forecast = model.predict(future)

# Plot forecast
fig1 = model.plot(forecast)
plt.title('Prophet Forecast: SOC Prediction')
plt.xlabel("Datetime")
plt.ylabel("SOC (%)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('../figures/prophet_forecast.png')
plt.show()
